One promising solution is the layer-wise training approach, where a model is systematically trained one layer at a time, gradually increasing its depth.
The term “layer” can refer to either an individual layer or a block comprising multiple layers.
In layer-wise training, only a single layer is active at a time for training, significantly reducing computation requirements.
Moreover, only the active layer needs to be exchanged with the server, further reducing communication costs.
Table 1 shows a significant reduction in a client’s resource requirements for layer-wise training compared to end-to-end training.

Although layer-wise training significantly reduces resource requirements, it may not be able to match the performance of end-to-end training as shown in Table 1.
In each stage of layer-wise training, a new layer is sequentially attached to the model, and all preceding layers are frozen, excluding them from further updates.
Given a fixed number of FL rounds for each stage, it can be challenging to train the newly added layer to work seamlessly with the previous layers, especially if the number of rounds is small.
Although increasing the number of rounds could potentially alleviate this problem, it would impose extra communication and computation overhead on the clients, canceling the benefits of layer-wise training.

Firstly, we discuss the pure layer-wise training baseline, referred to as LW-FedMoCoV3.
Figure 1 illustrates the local training process of LW-FedMoCoV3 across different stages.
For an encoder F𝐹F with a total of S𝑆S layers, the training process is divided into S𝑆S stages. Each stage s∈[1,S]𝑠1𝑆s\in[1,S] runs for a fixed number of FL communication rounds, Rssubscript𝑅𝑠R_{s}.
The training process starts with an empty encoder F𝐹F, and each stage s𝑠s sequentially adds a new layer Lssubscript𝐿𝑠L_{s} to F𝐹F, gradually increasing its depth.
During stage s𝑠s, only the corresponding layer Lssubscript𝐿𝑠L_{s} is updated, while all prior layers L1subscript𝐿1L_{1} to Ls−1subscript𝐿𝑠1L_{s-1} within F𝐹F are frozen, serving only for inference.
This strategy saves memory and computation, benefiting resource-constrained devices in FL environments.
Moreover, in each communication round, clients are only required to send the active layer Lssubscript𝐿𝑠L_{s} (and the MLP heads) to the server for aggregation. Likewise, the server only needs to broadcast the aggregated layer Lssubscript𝐿𝑠L_{s} back to clients. This reduces both upload and download communication costs for clients. Although layer-wise training offers better resource efficiency than end-to-end training, there remains a notable performance gap in linear evaluation, as we have shown in Table 1.

Table 2 compares the performance of different approaches. In terms of linear evaluation, LW-FedSSL demonstrates comparable performance to the end-to-end training of FedMoCoV3 and significantly outperforms the purely layer-wise training of LW-FedMoCoV3.
LW-FedSSL also outperforms or holds a competitive position against FedMoCoV3 in fine-tuning.
The progressive training approach, Prog-FedSSL, outperforms all other approaches in both linear evaluation and fine-tuning performance.
Interestingly, the fine-tuning performance of FedMoCoV3 is even lower than that of LW-FedMoCoV3 in some cases.
Please note that we apply the same fine-tuning settings, which may not be optimal for all approaches.
